Author: University of Minnesota PreCalculus Dept.
Reviewed/Remixed by: Doenet team

About the problem: Determine how many ways to choose k problems on a test with a bank of n questions. Application of the standard formula for combinations.
This problem is randomized with k ranging from 3 to 5 and n ranging from 5 (k = 3, b = 2) to 10 (k = 5, b = 5).
The Worked Example can be hidden by commenting out the <hint> portion of the document.
*************************************************************-->


<problem>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="3" to="5"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="2" to="5"/>
  <math name="n" simplify>$k + $b</math>
  <math name="binomkOfN">$n!/($k!$b!)</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>n = $n</p>
<p>k = $k</p>
<p>binomkOfN = $binomkOfN</p> -->
<!--testing-->
  
<p>An essay test consists of <m>$n</m> questions, of which you are to choose <m>$k</m> of them to answer. In how many ways can you choose the <m>$k</m> questions?</p> 
  <p><m>\text{Number of ways to choose questions} = </m>
      
    <answer name="ans9" >
      <mathInput name="userInput"/> 
      <award name="correct" symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare credit="1">    
        <when>
      $userInput=$binomkOfN
        </when>
      </award>
    </answer>
  </p>

